idates the complicated relationship between religion and national consciousness in the modern world, highlighting various cases in Central and Eastern Europe. Though those analyses, the authors show how religion, far from disappearing, strongly impacted the emerging national consciousness. Starting with the pre-modern era in this region, the book examines the long-term transformation of religious, political, and social situations of the region. In addition, the book considers the impact of imperial powers, which tended to be linked with a universal religion. It finally sheds light on the multifaceted nature of nations in this region, which contributes to evoke a new vision of the historical transformation of the region that enriches the general theories of nationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCentral Europeans. 0aChurch and statezEurope, CentralxHistoryv19th century. 0aNational characteristics, Central European. 0aNationalismxEurope, CentralxHistoryv19th century. 0aNationalismzEurope, CentralxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  a19th century.  a20th century.  aBaltic states.  aBelarus.  aCatholicism.  aCentral Eastern Europe.  aChristianity.  aCzech.  aEmpire.  aHabsburg.  aHistory.  aLithuania.  aOrthodox Church.  aPoland.  aReformation.  aRomanov.  aRussia.  aSoviet.  aUSSR.  aUniate.  aborderlands.  aclass.  aclergy.  aconfession.  aethnicity.  ahistoriography.  aidentity.  amodernization.  anationalism.  apolitics.  apre-WWI.  areligion.  areligious tradition.  aresistance.  arites.  asocial science.1 aAoshima, Yoko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAoshima, Yoko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBystryk, Aliaksandr, econtribut